                <article class="article">
                    <h2 class="headline">Local Developer Reinvents Digital Portfolio with Classic Newspaper Design</h2>
                    <p class="byline">By Amanda Chen, Technology Editor</p>
                    
                    <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1555066931-4365d14bab8c?ixlib=rb-4.0.3&auto=format&fit=crop&w=800&q=40" alt="Developer at work" class="image-left">
                    
                    <div class="two-column-text">
                        <p>SAN FRANCISCO - In an industry dominated by minimalist designs and template-based portfolios, local web developer John Doe has taken a radically different approach by transforming his professional portfolio into a fully-functional digital newspaper.</p>
                        
                        <p>The innovative design, which Doe calls "The Daily Portfolio," features traditional newspaper elements including multi-column layouts, serif typography, grayscale images, and classic newspaper sections - all while showcasing modern web development skills.</p>
                        
                        <div class="pull-quote">
                            This isn't just another portfolio. It's a statement about the enduring power of print design in a digital world.
                        </div>
                        
                        <p>"I wanted to create something that would stand out from the thousands of identical portfolio websites," Doe explained in an exclusive interview. "The newspaper format allows me to present my work in a narrative format that tells a story about my skills and experience."</p>
                        
                        <p>The portfolio includes traditional newspaper sections like classifieds, advertisements, and even a weather box - all repurposed to showcase Doe's technical abilities and professional background.</p>
                        
                        <p>Industry experts have praised the innovative approach. "In a sea of similarity, John's portfolio immediately captures attention," said tech recruiter Sarah Johnson. "It demonstrates both technical skill and creative thinking - exactly what employers are looking for."</p>
                    </div>
                </article>
                
